the fact of delousing; people would supposedly remove all the vermin from their body and their clothes and in a few minutes would find them again on themselves],"},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "2423.614","u": "Yes."},    {"who": "Udel Stopnitsky", "start": "2423.883","u": ". . . that we should be able to get rid of them, these run-overs [he uses the German word Umlauf which the prisoners may have adapted to mean &#34;being run over with vermin&#34;] . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "2426.803","u": "What is that?"},    {"who": "Udel Stopnitsky", "start": "2427.319","u": "Lice, flea, bedbugs, worms, everything you ever can think of, because there we didn&#39;t sleep anymore in beds. There we were lying stretched out on the floor with a little bit of straw under us, and that is how we were lying for three weeks. During this time the transport of seven thousand people to which we belonged was reduced to four thousand. The three thousand people were either shot during the march or have died out in the lager. And in February [he gives the Polish name apparently for February and that explains the question below], I don&#39;t remember exactly on what day, we had to abandon Gross-Rosen also, because . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "2458.094","u": "What month was it?"},    {"who": "Udel Stopnitsky", "start": "2459.080","u": "[He gives here the Polish name and then translates] In February, the second month."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "2462.938","u": "In &#39;45?"},    {"who": "Udel Stopnitsky", "start": "2463.957","u": "All that happened already in &#39;45."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "2465.413","u": "Yes."},    {"who": "Udel Stopnitsky", "start": "2465.967","u": "We got out of the lager and we started again to travel in trains. They loaded us into trains and we were traveling as if with no destination [I am not sure of the translation of the last two words]. They loaded us in open gondolas and here the snow and rain poured down from heaven as if without mercy and we were not getting anymore any food at all. And every morning when we, so to speak, got up, when we opened our eyes with daybreak, we had to throw out of the car two, three people because they had died overnight. Whether they had frozen to death or something else has happened. And so we traveled for eleven days, in on one station, out on the other station, until at the fifteenth day, it was the beginning of March, we arrived in the famous lager                         Flossenburg, that is at the border, of the Austrian-Czech border, a city. The lager was located on a mountain of about 1500 meters high. It was something terrible in that lager. When we . . . by the time we entered that lager there remained of us no more than seventeen hundred people."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "2522.496","u": "From how many?"},    {"who": "Udel Stopnitsky", "start": "2523.168","u": "From the seven thousand that left [originally] the lager. Three thousand fell during the march to Gross-Rosen, since Gross-Rosen fell two thousand three hundred people. And so . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "2531.443","u": "How does one know the numbers so exactly?"},    {"who": "Udel Stopnitsky", "start": "2533.386","u": "One doesn&#39;t know exactly; one estimates the number of people. For sure the number is not known; one cannot remember exactly. I know the people who fell from among my acquaintances, but I cannot remember the thousands of Jews [who fell.] Exactly is known that we arrived four thousand to Gross-Rosen, and seventeen hundred . . . When we arrived at Gross-Rosen they took us to a special sector and they knew exactly [how many]. They took us into a barracks; they told us to undress completely naked, that was in March, and they ordered us to run. We were running, seventeen hundred people entirely naked [this apparently happened already in Flossenburg; this kind of jumps from one topic to the other happened of course frequently in these interviews]."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "2563.248","u": "Inside the barracks?"},    {"who": "Udel Stopnitsky", "start": "2563.848","u": "Outside, in the lager, through the streets of the lager. After we have run four, five, possibly 600 meters uphill, we were led in a kind of washroom they called it , a kind of a cellar up there, so when we got up there&#226;down [in the cellar on the hill] . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "2576.775","u": "So you were running to the washroom?"},    {"who": "Udel Stopnitsky", "start": "2578.853","u": "To the washroom. From the &#34;undress-room&#34; [he repeats], &#34;undress-room&#34; to the washroom, 700 meters, we ran completely naked, in snow, in water, in mud . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "2585.180","u": "Men only?"},    {"who": "Udel Stopnitsky", "start": "2586.032","u": "Men only, seventeen hundred men. We got into the washroom, and there stood Ukrainians, also internees, and with cold, such what do they call it, cold hoses with which one pours water . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "2599.459","u": "Yes."},    {"who": "Udel Stopnitsky", "start": "2599.723","u": "They poured water all over us. The windows were open and soon, momentarily, people started to die."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "2605.428","u": "Why?"},    {"who": "Udel Stopnitsky", "start": "2606.212","u": "Of exhaustion, from not having eaten for fifteen days, in fifteen days we had but 60 deca of bread. [That totals up to 600 grams or a little bit better than a pound of bread.] For all the fifteen days 60 deca of bread."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "2613.531","u": "But how can one be for fifteen days with only 60 deca of bread?"},    {"who": "Udel Stopnitsky", "start": "2615.797","u": "People ate . . . one would find a little piece of turnip . . . for instance every night we spent in a different place."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "2620.562","u": "Yes."},    {"who": "Udel Stopnitsky",